This is because I was on course for early graduation and was interested in taking on the challenge of designing an end-to-end data science project from scratch independently. The final product consisted of a full stack project I designed using Plotly, an interactive Python library which I accessed using Jupyter Notebook. After creating the visualizations, I output the code as HTML and used front end programming to embed the interactive visualizations into a bootstrapped website I designed. The project was an extensive effort and a labor of love that spanned many months to almost a year from conception to writing the capstone to designing the models and slowly constructing the final product deliverable. Although it was incredibly challenging, I enjoyed learning in detail about machine learning models and getting my hands deep into code (Python, HTML, CSS, JavaScript via Mapbox API) to design a full stack project. I painstakingly coordinated with the client via phone and did extensive research into their industry including an over forty page literature review in addition to writing several drafts of the capstone report which constituted about sixty pages of technical data science concepts. I cared deeply about the client’s mission and invested my time and energy into designing a tool that made their work easier to do. The final product deliverable was used by the client for marketing and educational purposes. Following my presentation, I answered technical questions from a panel of judges and the audience.

Cyber Breach Analysis: A Global Overview¶

by Loretta Agyemang

Advancements in technology have resulted in the mass production of individual and corporate data. This digital resource has become a valuable commodity used to make decisions in all domains. The volume and velocity of data travel across the internet, an unregulated global public good, has presented an opportunity for malicious actors to commit financial fraud or to carry out cyber espionage as state actors. Hacking, social media manipulation, phishing and other internet scams have become serious problems facing individual citizens as well as private and public entities. The effects of sustained cyber attacks have resulted in an enviornment of mistrust and anxiety concerning data privacy. At the state level, cyber attacks on electoral systems have contributed to the errosion of trust in the democratic process. As the cyber threat landscape develops, it is important to provide a contextual overview of major breaches. Before delving into this information, it is necessary to understand why it's so challenging to contain cyber risk.

Mitigating cyber risk is challenging for the following reasons:

  • Lack of Transparancy:
    • Following a cyber breach, private and public targets react by hiding details. Sharing information about a breach occurance may give insight into the effected entity's cybersecurity infrastructure thereby creating opportunities for another attack. Sharing a breach occurance may also negatively impact a firm's reputation.

  • Assymetric Responses:
    • Cyber attackers carry out indiscriminate breaches but large, wealthy companies have the resources to better defend themselves against breaches. Exploiting weaknesses in the security infrastructures of smaller firms and individuals can prepare a hacker to carry out larger scale projects.

  • Limited Regulation:
    • Although cyber security frameworks have been constructed by organizations like the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) and the Information Security Organization for Standardization (ISO), these policies have not been universally adopted. To date, there is no commonly shared regulatory practice.

    Data Preparation¶

    The following is an analysis of major cybersecurity breaches from 2004 to the present (2019). Data comes from an interactive visualization created by David McCandless and Tom Evans using VizSweet Balloon Race with research by Miriam Quick, Ella Hollowood, Christian Miles and Dan Hampson: https://informationisbeautiful.net/visualizations/worlds-biggest-data-breaches-hacks/

    After downloading their source data from a shared Google sheet, I cleaned entries using Excel. I validated the number of records lost by conducting my own searches. A new column titled "Country" was engineered after researching where the target entity operates. For cases where the breach impacted individuals and businesses in several different countries, the term "International" was used. Additionally, I renamed the columns and made the details about the stolen records more succinct.

def CtyGrp(Country):
    if Country in A:
        return 'AsiaPacific' 
    elif Country in B:
        return 'Europe'
    elif Country in C:
        return 'MiddleEastAfrica'
    elif Country in D:
        return 'NorthAmerica'
    elif Country in E:
        return 'SouthAmerica'
    else: 
        return 'International'

    Breach Method¶

    Cybercriminals have become increasingly sophisticated. Opensource technologies provide resources for attackers to learn how to develop more dangerous tools using machine learning and artificial intelligence. They are often confident that their actions will continue undetected since studies have shown that it takes an average of about 200 days for a targeted organization to detect a data breach (https://www.itgovernanceusa.com/blog/how-long-does-it-take-to-detect-a-cyber-attack). Holding malicious actors accountable for their actions is also challenging because there is a long standing cyber workforce shortage.

    Cyber criminals employ a number of tactics to exploit structural weaknesses in a firm or individual's cybersecurity infrastructure. Some key theat vectors include: Account hijacking, phishing, Potentially Unwanted Program (PUP) Adware, ransomeware/malware and unpatched systems.

    The majority of the firms that experienced breaches in this dataset were impacted by hackings.

    This article from PheonixNap, a global IT service, provides more expert insight into trends in the cybersecurity space: https://phoenixnap.com/blog/cybersecurity-experts-threats-trends

    Cyber Breach Financial Impact¶

    From case studies conducted using stock prices of firms that have publically declared a breach occurance (from internal human errors, lost tapes or malicious actors), it appears that the public learning about a breach may result in an immediate dip in closing prices. This drop, however, is often temporary. Once the firm as able to show that efforts are being made to contain the breach, stock prices often bounce back.The costs of cleaning up a fallout from a breach are more consequential than a temporary threat to stock prices.

    Some costs associated with major data breaches include detection costs, communications and PR outreach costs, costs of putting together logistics teams to contain and mitigate the situation as well as opportunity costs associated with the breach. Following a breach, churn rates may increase as customers become nervous about their information being stolen. Smaller firms have much more to lose from a cyber breach because they have less resources to protect themselves from an impending attack and their revenue can take a bigger hit when the public hears that their data was breached.

    More information about monitoring to detect data breaches and setting up security IT infrastructure as defensive mechanisms can be found here: https://www.brighttalk.com/webcast/11871/350825?utm_medium=web&utm_source=brighttalk-promoted&utm_campaign=knowledge-feed

                x=df.Date,
                y=df['High'],
                name = "Stock High",
                line = dict(color = '#17BECF'),
                opacity = 0.8)

trace_low = go.Scatter(
                x=df.Date,
                y=df['Low'],
                name = "Stock Low",
                line = dict(color = '#7F7F7F'),
                opacity = 0.8)

data = [trace_high,trace_low]

layout = dict(
    title = "Tracking Stock Prices During Breach",
    xaxis = dict(
        range = ['2018-04-09','2019-01-28'])
)

fig = dict(data=data, layout=layout)
py.iplot(fig, filename = "Manually Set Range")
    Out[10]:

    Shares for this major brand dropped by about 5% immediatly following news that private customer data had been compromised. Using stock prices as an indicator for fallout from a cyber breach may be challenging because causality cannot be implied directly. For example, around the time the public was updated about breach details, sales in a major market declined due to unrelated events. It is likely that share holders may have reacted to this news as well.

    Data for this stock analysis came from Yahoo Finance. Due to the sensitive nature of cyber security breaches, a decision was made in this particular analysis and interactive data visualization to anonymize the information and not reveal company names.

    Sentiment Analysis (explicitly customized)¶

    Valence Aware Dictionary and sEntiments Reasoner (VADER)¶

    https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/simplifying-social-media-sentiment-analysis-using-vader-in-python-f9e6ec6fc52f
    Lexicon and rule-based sentiment analysis tool that is tuned to sentiments expressed in social media. "VADER has been found to be quite successful when dealing with social media texts, NY Times editorials, movie reviews, and product reviews. This is because VADER not only tells about the Positivity and Negativity score but also tells us about how positive or negative a sentiment is."

    • Works well on social media types
    • Doesn't require training data
    • Fast & scalable
    • Impacted by use of punctuation and sentance structure
      • Exclamation: "The use of an exclamation mark(!), increases the magnitude of the intensity without modifying the semantic orientation."
      • Capitalization: "For example, “The food here is GREAT!” conveys more intensity than “The food here is great!"
      • Degree modifiers: “The service here is extremely good” is more intense than “The service here is good”, whereas “The service here is marginally good” reduces the intensity.
      • Conjunction: “The food here is great, but the service is horrible” has mixed sentiment, with the latter half dictating the overall rating.
      • Preceding Tri-gram: "By examining the tri-gram preceding a sentiment-laden lexical feature, we catch nearly 90% of cases where negation flips the polarity of the text."
      • Emojis, Slangs & Emoticons: performs very well and captures sentiments
    In [103]:
    analyzer = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
    In [104]:
    def sentiment_analyzer_scores(sentence):
    score = analyzer.polarity_scores(sentence)
    print("{:-<40} {}".format(sentence, str(score)))

    Topic Detection Modeling¶

    Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) Model¶

    Latent Dirichlet (LDA) Models is a type of topic modeling that represents statistical models that allows sets of observations that are used to classify text in a document to a specific topic.

    In [48]:
    # Initialize the modules to normalize text using lemmatizer 

lem = WordNetLemmatizer()
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
ex = set(string.punctuation)

for w in ['Chicago', 'Illinois', 'state']:
    stop_words.add(w)


# Function to clean document 

def cleaning(doc):
    nstopwd = " ".join([i for i in doc.lower().split() if i not in stop_words])
    npunct = ''.join(ch for ch in nstopwd if ch not in ex)
    norm = " ".join(lem.lemmatize(word) for word in npunct.split())
    return norm

df2['title_clean'] = [cleaning(doc).split() for doc in df2.text.to_list()]
df2['text_clean'] = [cleaning(doc).split() for doc in df2.text.to_list()]

    Using Functions and Aggregating Data¶

    Wrote query to filter the product returned so that only products with a numeric size are included.

    In [ ]:
    SELECT ProductID, UPPER(Name) AS ProductName, ROUND(Weight, 0) AS ApproxWeight,
       YEAR(SellStartDate) AS SellStartYear,
       DATENAME(m, SellStartDate) AS SellStartMonth,
       LEFT(ProductNumber, 2) AS ProductType
FROM SalesLT.Product
-- filter for numeric product size data
WHERE ISNUMERIC(Size) = 1;

    Wrote query that returns a list of company names with a ranking of their place in a list of highest values from table.

    SELECT CompanyName, TotalDue AS Revenue,
       -- get ranking and order 
       RANK() OVER (ORDER BY TotalDue DESC) AS RankByRevenue
FROM SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader AS SOH
-- join tables
INNER JOIN SalesLT.Customer AS C
ON SOH.CustomerID = C.CustomerID;

    Using Subqueries and APPLY¶

    Wrote query to retrieve the product ID, name, and list price for each product where the list price is higher than the average unit price for all products that have been sold.

    In [ ]:
    SELECT ProductID, Name, ListPrice 
FROM SalesLT.Product
-- filter based on ListPrice
WHERE ListPrice > 
-- get the average UnitPrice
(SELECT AVG(UnitPrice) FROM SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail)
ORDER BY ProductID;

    Wrote query and included aliases to retrieve the customer ID, first name, last name, address line 1 and city for all customers from the SalesLT.Address and SalesLT.CustomerAddress tables, using the dbo.ufnGetCustomerInformation function.

    In [ ]:
    SELECT CA.CustomerID, CI.FirstName, CI.LastName, A.Addressline1, A.City
FROM SalesLT.Address AS A
JOIN SalesLT.CustomerAddress AS CA
-- join based on AddressID
ON A.AddressID = CA.AddressID
-- cross apply as per instructions
CROSS APPLY dbo.ufnGetCustomerInformation(CA.CustomerID) AS CI
ORDER BY CA.CustomerID;

    Grouping Sets & Pivoting Data¶

    Wrote query to include a grand total in results for all sales revenue and a subtotal for each country/region in addition to the state/province subtotals that are already returned.

    In [ ]:
    SELECT a.CountryRegion, a.StateProvince, SUM(soh.TotalDue) AS Revenue
FROM SalesLT.Address AS a
JOIN SalesLT.CustomerAddress AS ca
ON a.AddressID = ca.AddressID
JOIN SalesLT.Customer AS c
ON ca.CustomerID = c.CustomerID
JOIN SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader as soh
ON c.CustomerID = soh.CustomerID
-- Modify GROUP BY to use ROLLUP
GROUP BY ROLLUP(a.CountryRegion, a.StateProvince) 
ORDER BY a.CountryRegion, a.StateProvince;

    Edited query to include a grouping for individual cities.

    In [ ]:
    SELECT a.CountryRegion, a.StateProvince, a.City,
CHOOSE (1 + GROUPING_ID(a.CountryRegion) + GROUPING_ID(a.StateProvince) + GROUPING_ID(a.City),
        a.City + ' Subtotal', a.StateProvince + ' Subtotal',
        a.CountryRegion + ' Subtotal', 'Total') AS Level,
SUM(soh.TotalDue) AS Revenue
FROM SalesLT.Address AS a
JOIN SalesLT.CustomerAddress AS ca
ON a.AddressID = ca.AddressID
JOIN SalesLT.Customer AS c
ON ca.CustomerID = c.CustomerID
JOIN SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader as soh
ON c.CustomerID = soh.CustomerID
GROUP BY ROLLUP(a.CountryRegion, a.StateProvince, a.City)
ORDER BY a.CountryRegion, a.StateProvince, a.City;

    Wrote query to retrieve a list of customer company names together with their total revenue for each parent category in Accessories, Bikes, Clothing, and Components.

    In [ ]:
    SELECT * FROM
(SELECT cat.ParentProductCategoryName, cust.CompanyName, sod.LineTotal
 FROM SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail AS sod
 JOIN SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader AS soh ON sod.SalesOrderID = soh.SalesOrderID
 JOIN SalesLT.Customer AS cust ON soh.CustomerID = cust.CustomerID
 JOIN SalesLT.Product AS prod ON sod.ProductID = prod.ProductID
 JOIN SalesLT.vGetAllCategories AS cat ON prod.ProductcategoryID = cat.ProductCategoryID) AS catsales
PIVOT (SUM(LineTotal) FOR ParentProductCategoryName
IN ([Accessories], [Bikes], [Clothing], [Components])) AS pivotedsales
ORDER BY CompanyName;

    Programming with Transact-SQL + Error Handling & Transactions¶

    Created reusable scripts that make it easy to insert sales orders and order detail.

    In [ ]:
    -- Declare variables 
DECLARE @OrderDate datetime = GETDATE();
DECLARE @DueDate datetime = DATEADD(dd, 7, GETDATE());
DECLARE @CustomerID int = 1;
INSERT INTO SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader (OrderDate, DueDate, CustomerID, ShipMethod)
VALUES (@OrderDate, @DueDate, @CustomerID, 'CARGO TRANSPORT 5');
DECLARE @OrderID int = SCOPE_IDENTITY();


DECLARE @SalesOrderID int 
DECLARE @ProductID int = 760;
DECLARE @Quantity int = 1;
DECLARE @UnitPrice money = 782.99;

SET @SalesOrderID = 0; 

-- If statement to insert values 
IF EXISTS (SELECT * FROM SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader WHERE SalesOrderID = @SalesOrderID)
BEGIN
	INSERT INTO SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail (SalesOrderID, OrderQty, ProductID, UnitPrice)
	VALUES (@OrderID, @Quantity, @ProductID, @UnitPrice)
END
ELSE
BEGIN
	PRINT 'The order does not exist'
END

    Wrote script to log errors while implementing a T-SQL script to delete orders.

    In [ ]:
    DECLARE @OrderID int = 0

-- Declare a custom error if the specified order doesn't exist
DECLARE @error VARCHAR(30) = 'Order #' + cast(@OrderID as VARCHAR) + ' does not exist';

IF NOT EXISTS(SELECT * FROM SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader WHERE SalesOrderID = @OrderID)
BEGIN
  THROW 50001, @error, 0;
END
ELSE
BEGIN
  DELETE FROM SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail WHERE SalesOrderID = @OrderID;
  DELETE FROM SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader WHERE SalesOrderID = @OrderID;
END
